# The downloaded asset payloads are NOT committed. autom-deps fetches them from
# their upstream archives on demand (see the asset entries in kreate/AUTOMDEPS),
# which keeps ~650MB of art out of git history and out of every clone.
#
# What IS committed, and must stay committed:
#
#   * each asset's LICENSE.txt / license.txt — Sketchfab does not put the license
#     inside the downloadable zip, so it exists nowhere but here. If it is lost,
#     the attribution obligation goes with it and the asset's provenance becomes
#     unreconstructible. This is the one file autom-deps cannot re-fetch.
#   * orange_tennis_racket/ in full — it was generated with Meshy AI rather than
#     downloaded, so there is no upstream URL to pull it from. It has to live in
#     the tree (through LFS; see .gitattributes).
#   * this file, .gitattributes, and README.md.

# Ignore the contents of every asset folder...
/*/**

# ...but keep the provenance that cannot be re-downloaded.
!/*/LICENSE.txt
!/*/license.txt

# The racket has no download link, so it stays in-tree in full.
!/orange_tennis_racket/**

# Wavefront meshes are not compiled object files.
#
# Both the root .gitignore and kreate/.gitignore carry a `*.obj` rule aimed at
# MSVC object files, and it cannot tell a compiler artifact from a mesh. It was
# silently swallowing the .obj models here — `git add` reported success while the
# geometry never entered the index, and the loss would only have surfaced as a
# failing test on a fresh clone. The negation is kept (it is moot while the
# payloads are ignored) so the trap cannot reappear if an asset is ever committed
# directly.
!*.obj
